post_text:
Reagan County ISD UIL/COVID-19 Extracurricular Activity Guidelines

• We understand support by parents and fans is an important part of these activities. We also understand that to continue to have these activities there are specific guidelines we must follow.

• Students in grades PK-5th, as well as pre-school age children will be required to be accompanied by an adult and remain seated with an adult.

• Students in grades 6th – 8th will be required to be accompanied by an adult to be admitted to the event.

• All spectators will be required to perform a self-screening process prior to attending all events.

• All spectators will be required to maintain proper distancing and/or wear a face covering.

• The stadium and gymnasium capacity will be limited to 50% of the maximum seating capacity.

post_text: Please help stop the spread of COVID-19. If you have been in close contact with someone that has tested positive for COVID-19, please do not attend any school related activities or athletic events. Current public health and Reagan County ISD requirements include self-monitoring of symptoms and exclusion from all public settings such as school and/or school activities for 14 days since the last known exposure. If you experience symptoms of COVID-19 then it is recommended you should seek medical advice and isolate yourself from others for 14 days. A negative test result during the 14-day self-monitoring period does not suffice to shorten this required quarantine period. Thanks for helping keep our students and staff safe!

post_text: On Friday, August 21st we received confirmation that three Reagan County High School students tested positive for COVID 19. We will notify the parents of students that might have been exposed to anyone that tested positive for COVID-19. A mask or face covering can help prevent your student from being exposed. We highly recommend that everyone wears a face covering when within six feet of others. If you suspect your child was in close contact with an individual that tested positive, we are asking everyone to be upfront and honest by notifying the school. Together we can prevent the spread of COVID-19!

post_text: This is a message from the Superintendent, Mr. Fryar. We have been informed that a Reagan County ISD employee has tested positive for COIVD-19. The employee will self-quarantine for the time recommended by the CDC. Any employee who has had close contact with infected employee will also self-quarantine for the time recommended by the CDC. We have disinfected all areas in the district the infected employee has visited. We have notified the Public Health Officials; we have also notified all other district employees.

post_text: For elementary students that are paper-based while we are distance learning, there will be containers outside the main entrance on Monday from 9:00am-5:00pm. For each grade-level there is a container to return completed work and a separate container to pick up the new packet for the week. In the event of an extension of our distance learning, we will follow this same procedure every week. Remember this is only for those that are NOT participating in the online distance learning. For those of you that have gone digital, your new assignments will continue to show up in your Google Classroom. If you come pick up a packet, please be considerate and make sure you are practicing social distancing if others are here to pick up.

post_text:
Reagan County ISD--Disinfecting of Campuses

I have no doubt that you are aware of the Coronavirus or COVID-19. You have heard numerous news media outlets discussing this over the last several days. RCISD contracts with GermBlast, a professional disinfectant company to disinfect our campuses and buses three times a year. GremBlast disinfected every building and bus during the week of Spring Break. For more information about GremBlast you can go to their website germblast.com. Rest assured that our campuses have been disinfected and cleaned, ready for child to return to school on Monday, March 16th. If you have any questions or concerns, please don't hesitate to give us a call. Thank you, for allowing us to educate your children!

Bobby Fryar, Superintendent

post_text:
Community School Safety Meeting on November 4th, 2019 from 6:00PM to 6:30PM in the High School Cafeteria
Reagan County ISD would like to welcome community members and parents to attend our community school safety meeting on November 4th at 6:00PM in the High School Cafeteria. We will discuss ways to recognize possible threats and how to report incidents. We need community support to report any situation that might be viewed as a threat for our school campuses. Everyone has a role to recognize concerns, respond in a helpful manner, and to report concerns to persons who can best help the situation. Reagan County ISD has multiple reporting procedures for community members: Online, By Phone, or Directly
